NEWS: $TSLA's FSD Tech Breaks Through Challenges for Open-Road Testing in China

• 8 main districts in Hangzhou, China will be made available to pilot tests of self-driving vehicles from May 1, according to a report by local outlet Qianjiang Evening News.

• The regulation doesn't specify the exact level of autonomous driving allowed, but previously permits for up to L4 autonomy have been granted.

• Hangzhou is the first city in China to define the specific process for autonomous vehicles on public roads through local legislation, and it is also the first city to enact laws for low-speed unmanned vehicles.

• In Beijing and Shanghai, autonomous driving is still only allowed in the outer suburbs, while just 5% of central Guangzhou is open for autonomous driving.

• Tesla is looking to get approval to test Robotaxi in Shanghai but needs clearance from Chinese regulators before it can fully roll out FSD and collect the data required to train the software.
